Abstract

Black and white ruffed lemurs (_Varecia variegata_) are a critically endangered primate species endemic to Madagascar's eastern rainforests, playing a crucial role as primary seed dispersers in their ecosystem. However, they are considered more sensitive to forest modification than many other lemur species and have historically been extirpated from areas with intensive logging operations. This study aims to investigate how habitat quality influences the vocal behaviour of _V. variegata_ by employing an innovative, multidisciplinary approach combining Passive Acoustic Monitoring (PAM), behavioural observations, and advanced deep learning techniques.

Madagascar's rapidly degrading forests pose significant threats the habitats of many lemur populations, potentially altering their social structures, behaviour, and vocal communication patterns. By examining vocalization patterns across different habitat gradients within Ranomafana National Park and the COVAF corridor, this research will explore how environmental changes impact lemur acoustic communication. The study will focus on two primary hypotheses: first, that lemurs in degraded forests use a higher proportion of alarm calls; second, that acoustic properties can predict post call behaviour.

Utilizing Audiomoth recorders, focal follows, and a convolutional neural network for call classification, the research will extract detailed acoustic parameters and behavioural context. Together, these features of the RNP-COVAF region offer an excellent locality to evaluate the role of environmental variation on ruffed lemur dispersal and functional connectivity. By integrating bioacoustics, machine learning, and ecological monitoring, this study seeks to provide critical insights into vocal communication as a potential bio-indicator of ecosystem health and species adaptation to environmental stress.

# Introduction

Black and white ruffed lemurs (Varecia variegata) are critically endangered primate species endemic to Madagascar's eastern rainforests. As keystone species and primary seed dispersers, they maintain forest biodiversity by transporting large seeds over relatively long distances, dispersing up to 40 different tree species, and increasing germination rates by up to 300% (Razafindratsima et al., 2014; Moses & Semple, 2011).

Madagascar's forests are undergoing rapid degradation through deforestation, fragmentation, and increasing anthropogenic pressures (Harper et al., 2007), with 45% of its original forest cover removed over the past 60 years (Hending et al., 2022). The ruffed lemur appears particularly vulnerable to habitat changes compared to other lemur species, sometimes abstaining from breeding for up to four years when environmental conditions are not suitable (Ratsimbazafy, 2002; Baden et al., 2013). These environmental changes potentially alter their social structures, behaviour, and vocal communication patterns. Further population declines could trigger cascading effects on ecosystem function, forest regeneration, and long-term stability.

Black and White ruffed lemurs reside in a highly flexible social structure and live in groups with strong fission-fusion dynamics, with individuals moving fluidly between subgroups depending on food resources and social influences (Baden et al., 2015). Their diverse vocal repertoire—comprising 11 distinct call types, eight of which appear in various combinations—is crucial for maintaining contact within and among subgroups in dense tropical forests where visual communication is limited (Pereira et al., 1988; Batist et al., 2021). Understanding how habitat degradation influences vocalization patterns may provide insights into behavioural adaptations to environmental change (Ey & Fischer, 2009; Batist et al., 2023).

Passive Acoustic Monitoring (PAM) has emerged as a powerful, non-invasive tool in primatology, enabling researchers to collect more extensive data than traditionally possible. PAM allows for continuous, long-term monitoring of vocal behaviour without direct human presence, which can be particularly valuable for studying elusive species in difficult to navigate topography (Cauzinille et al., 2024). PAM has proved to be more effective compared to camera traps when studying other primates, offering a higher detection rate and needing less deployment time (Crunchant et al., 2020). It has also been shown to have equal or higher accuracy rates when compared to human based observations (Hoefer et al., 2023).

To complement PAM and ensure structural analysis of vocal behaviour, we will conduct focal follows using ethograms to categorize vocalizations within their behavioural context, providing insights into factors influencing social cohesion and alarm calls. Our study encompasses five sites across south-eastern Madagascar, representing a gradient of habitat quality from relatively pristine protected areas to heavily degraded forest fragments.

Recent advances in deep learning applications to bioacoustics have enhanced our ability to analyse primate vocalizations. These computational methods can process large PAM datasets, potentially uncovering patterns that traditional analysis might miss. Such models have already demonstrated promise in automating call detection and classification for V. variegata, improving research efficiency and scalability (Batist et al., 2024).

Despite the pressing conservation needs for this endangered species. There remains a significant knowledge gap regarding how habitat quality affects its behaviour, particularly vocal communication. As a highly social and vocally complex species, black-and-white ruffed lemurs rely on vocalizations for group cohesion, coordination, and predator avoidance (Fichtel & Kappeler, 2022). Given this reliance, shifts in vocal behaviour may serve as a key bio-indicator of environmental stress, habitat fragmentation, or behavioural adaptation in response to ecological change.

This study addresses the following research questions:

1. How do vocalization rates, types, and acoustic parameters differ between lemur populations in pristine versus degraded habitats?
2. Can specific vocal characteristics predict subsequent behavioural patterns in V. variegata?
3. To what extent does habitat quality influence the relationship between vocalization parameters and social behaviours?

Based on previous research on primate acoustic communication and habitat disturbance (Wich & Nunn, 2002; Irwin et al., 2010; Nascimento et al., 2021), this study tests two primary hypotheses.

1. Lemurs in degraded forests are expected to produce a higher proportion of alarm calls in response to increased environmental stressors.
2. Acoustic properties of roar-shriek calls can predict post-call behaviours, with a higher average frequency and for a shorter durations (&lt;3 seconds) associating with vigilance behaviours, while lower average frequencies and longer durations (&gt;5 seconds) preceding group cohesion behaviours (based on primary group resonse)—a relationship documented in other primates such as Guianan red howlers but not yet studied in lemurs (Nascimento et al., 2021).

We will further investigate whether habitat quality modifies the relationship between call acoustic parameters and post-call behaviours.

Results from this study will contribute to both primate bioacoustics and lemur conservation. Exploring vocal behaviour as a potential bio-indicator of ecosystem health and species viability, supporting non-invasive, data-driven approaches to wildlife monitoring and habitat assessment. By establishing baseline acoustic parameters for _V. variegata_ across habitat gradients, this research will enable future monitoring programs to detect early warning signs of population stress before demographic declines become evident, offering a tool for adaptive conservation management in a rapidly changing landscape.

# Methods

### Study Area

This study will be conducted in and around the area of Ranomafana National Park (RNP), a 41,000-hectare continuous rainforest located in southeastern Madagascar (21°16'S, 47°20'E). Established in 1991, RNP encompasses a range of habitats, from pristine primary forests to areas that have undergone varying degrees of degradation due to past logging activities (Wright et al. 2012). The park's mid-elevation tropical rainforest (800–1100 m) supports high levels of biodiversity, including the multiple communities of black-and-white ruffed lemur (_Varecia variegata_) throughout the region, occupying varying levels of habitat quality.

Fieldwork will take place at four distinct sites within RNP, each representing different levels of habitat disturbance and openly available data will be used from a fifth site, a wildlife corridor connected to the national park:

1. Mangevo (21.3833S, 47.4667E) – Pristine Forest

Mangevo is an undisturbed primary rainforest with no history of logging, it has a tall continuous canopy (25-30m). This site serves as the location for the long-term Ranomafana Ruffed Lemur Project and provides a critical baseline for understanding vocalization patterns in an intact habitat (Mancini 2023).

1. Talatakely – Selectively Logged Forest

Talatakely was heavily logged between 1986 and 1989. Although the forest has undergone regrowth, the canopy height remains lower (18–25 m) compared to pristine sites. The area includes research cabins, campsites, and an extensive trail network, making it an accessible location for studying the effects of past logging on lemur vocal behaviour (Wright and Andriamihaja [2002](https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-642-22514-7_4#ref-CR174_4)).

1. Valohoaka - Selectively Logged Forest

Valohoaka is a minimally disturbed site within RNP, characterized by selective logging prior to the establishment of the national park in 1991. This site has a structurally complex forest with a mixed canopy height of **20–30 m**, reflecting moderate levels of historical disturbance (Mancini 2023).

1. Sakaroa – heavily logged forest

Sakaroa is the most degraded study site within Ranomafana National Park. It experienced extensive anthropogenic disturbance prior to the park's formation in 1991. Historically, the site was primarily used for **rice cultivation and human habitation**, leaving little remaining forest cover before the park’s establishment. Since then, the area has undergone **natural regeneration,** though the forest remains structurally altered, with a **lower canopy height (10–20 m),** reduced basal area, and lower tree species diversity compared to less disturbed sites. (Mancini 2023).

1. COVAF Corridor –Degraded & Fragmented Forest

The Corridor Forestier d'Ambositra Vondrozo (COVAF) is an ecological corridor connecting multiple protected areas. This site is not protected and experiences ongoing human influence including logging and hunting. This area has undergone significant habitat degradation, making it ideal for assessing how extreme environmental changes impact lemur vocalizations. For this site we will use open source PAM data collected by another researcher in this region. The data was collected from December 2021 – June 2022 (Batist et. a, 2024).

At each site within RNP a minimum of five different autonomous recording units (ARUs) will be set up to ensure replication and as a safeguard increase some of the units' malfunction. Data will be collected for a minimum of 50 days at each site to account for daily variation within the vocal activity. For the COVAF corridor we will use recordings from ten independent locations.

### Study Species

The black and white ruffed lemurs make ideal candidates for study using PAM. Their loud chorus of roar-shriek calls echoes across the rainforest making it easily distinguishable for PAM and classifiable by the deep learning algorithm. The function of these calls appears to act like a head count among sub-groups where visibility is not possible. These calls tend to follow stressful situations and help maintain social cohesion within the community. Their function is still a topic of debate among experts (Batist et al., 2024; Pereira et al 1998). Another call that will be focused on is the bark which is a type of alarm call of the black and white ruffed lemur and is used as an alert for aerial or terrestrial predators (Macedonia, 1990).

## Data Collection Methods

### Acoustic Data Collection

To assess vocalization patterns, autonomous recording units (ARUs) will be deployed at various points throughout the study sites. The ARUs will consist of Audiomoth recorders, positioned within core habitat areas and spaced at a minimum of 1km apart. Roar-shrieks can be detected by Audiomoths up to and possibly beyond 400m (Batist et al., 2024) so they will be placed at least 1km apart to avoid pseudo replication. Additionally, close proximity to paths and rivers will be avoided as these may interfere with call identification.

This spacing will minimize redundant recordings while accounting for sound attenuation due to vegetation and topography. The devices will be placed at a height of 2–3 m in trees, secured with cable locks, and will be programmed to record continuously, 156 hours per day between 5am and 8pm. Battery and SD card checks will occur biweekly to ensure uninterrupted data collection. Two 128GB microSD cards will be needed for each device as well as an external power source. The Audiomoths have a sample rate of 48kHz, a gain of 30dB and record in a 16-bit mono format.

### Environmental Data Collection

To assess habitat quality, information of historical logging activities will be recorded, and vegetation surveys will be conducted at each ARU. These surveys will measure presence of food resources. Climate data, including temperature, humidity, and rainfall, will be obtained from local weather stations and recorded daily for each study site.

### Behavioural Observations

Focal sampling with instantaneous scan sampling will be conducted to collect in-person vocalization data (Altmann, 1974). This mixed method is often used in primate research to obtain an insight into their complex social structures (Fichtel & Kappeler, 2002; Kalan and Boesch 2015). The bark and the roar-shriek will be focused on as they are the two calls that can most reliably be picked up by our ARUs (Batist et al. 2024). Behavioural states will be recorded before and after our focus calls take place. Behaviours will be recorded based on call events. During focal observations, the behavioural state of the focal individual will be monitored based on call events, researcher will document behaviour for 30 seconds following any vocalization events. A group snapshot will be recorded 30 seconds following a call event. This monitoring method ensures that the contextual behaviours around spontaneous calls are captured accurately, even though calls cannot be predicted in advance. We will track individuals, from dawn to dusk (~8 am–5 pm) five days per week. Behavioural states will be recorded using a standardized ethogram and based of previous lemur behaviour studies (Altmann, 1974; Bolt et al., 2020).

## Behavioural Response Data

### Caller's Behaviour (immediately after vocalization)

- **Post-Call Behaviour**: Code from Behavioural State list
- **Movement**: Remained stationary/Approached others/Moved away/Fled
- **Gaze Direction**: Toward group/Toward external stimulus/Scanning

### Group Response

- **Number of Individuals Responding**: Count of lemurs showing any response
- **Primary Group Response**: No response/Vocalize/Approach caller/Move away/Increase vigilance
- **Latency to Response**: Immediate (&lt;3s)/Short (3-10s)/Delayed (&gt;10s)
- **Group Cohesion Change**: Increased/Decreased/No change

Contextual Factors

- **Apparent Stimulus**: Predator/Other species/Conspecific group/Human/Unknown
- **Distance to Stimulus**: Estimated in meters
- **Social Context**: Feeding competition/Territorial dispute/Predator encounter/Neutral
- **Nearest Neighbour**: Distance (m) to closest lemur at time of call
- **Height in Canopy**: Ground level/Lower/Middle/Upper canopy

Rare or significant encounters such as predator sightings or interactions with other species will recorded whenever they occur

## Data Analysis

### Preprocessing of Acoustic Data

One of the primary challenges in processing passive acoustic data is mitigating background noise from environmental and anthropogenic sources (Towsey et al., 2018). Raw field recordings will be, standardized, filtered and prepared for accurate classification and interpretation. Given the acoustic variance of our tropical soundscape preprocessing will address issues such as background noise, overlapping calls and variable signal quality.

1. Noise Reduction and Signal Enhancement

Spectral subtraction is a noise reduction technique which will improve the clarity of the focal calls by removing stationary noise from our call signals. The process will be performed using Fast Fourier Transform (FFT). Band pass filtering will be applied to isolate the relevant frequencies of for our call types and discard irrelevant background noise. From prior research we will filter in a range between 1 – 20 kHz (Batist, 2024).

1. Segmentation and Call detection

Accurate call segmentation before deep learning classification can greatly improve our model's accuracy while also reducing processing time. Segmentation will be performed using Raven Pro. This software provides multiple detectors that can be fine-tuned for different lemur calls. Calls will then be manually validated to refine detector setting and minimise false positives. Spectrograms will be generated using a Hann window function with standardised parameters. Hidden Markov Models (HMMs) is a statistical approach to model the sequential structure of calls. This method has proved to be effective in noisy environments and should further improve the models accuracy (Stowell & Plumbley, 2014).

1. Feature Extraction

Once calls are segmented, key acoustic parameters will be extracted to characterize vocalization patterns across different habitat types. The following features will be analysed:

- Fundamental Frequency (Hz): The lowest frequency of a call, indicative of species-specific vocal characteristics (Ey & Fischer, 2009).
- Formant Frequencies: Higher frequency resonances that provide insight into vocal tract modifications.
- Call Duration (s): Duration of vocal sequences, reflecting behavioural context and urgency.
- Spectral Entropy: Measures the complexity of a call, useful for distinguishing between alarm and contact calls.
- Amplitude Modulation (dB variation over time): Fluctuations in intensity, relevant for assessing emotional state or stress response.

### Deep Learning Based Call Classification

A convolutional neural network (CNN) will be employed to automate the classification of lemur vocalizations. Transfer learning will be utilized, leveraging a ResNet152V2 model pre-trained on ImageNet. The early convolutional layers will be frozen, while the final layers will be fine-tuned using a training dataset of manually labelled lemur calls. Model performance will be evaluated using precision-recall metrics, and misclassified spectrograms will be manually reviewed to refine classification accuracy. A randomly selected 10% of positively identified calls will be reviewed by trained experts for validation.

### Focal Follows

Behaviour data from the focal follows will be directly linked to acoustic parameters extracted from synchronized audio recordings. This will allow us to examine if there are any habitat-specific variations in the call structure and if there is any behaviour change based on the vocalization and habitat quality.

### Statistical Analyses

To test our hypotheses regarding the effects of habitat quality on black and white ruffed lemur (Varecia variegata) vocal behaviour, we will employ Generalized Linear Mixed Models (GLMMs). The analysis strategy considers the unique constraints of this study, including limited sample sites and the variability and complexity of acoustic ecological data recorded in tropical rainforests. For the purpose of this analysis we will assume that our 20 study sites are independent. In total we aim to have 30 study sites, our 20 study sites and 10 study sites from previous research conducted in 2022.

### Testing Hypothesis 1: Alarm Call Proportion

For our first hypothesis that lemurs in degraded forests produce a higher proportion of alarm calls, we will construct a binomial GLMM. The response variable will be the number of alarm calls relative to the total number of calls detected, structured as a binomial variable (success/failure counts). The primary fixed effect will be habitat quality with four levels representing our gradient of disturbance (pristine, selectively logged, heavily logged, and degraded/fragmented). Additional covariates will include temperature, rainfall, time of day, canopy cover, and group size to account for environmental and social factors that may influence calling behaviour. We will include a nested random effects structure (Area/Day), where recordings from the same day are nested within study sites. This structure addresses the non-independence of observations collected from the same location on the same day.

### Testing Hypothesis 2: Acoustic fingerprint of Behaviour

To test whether acoustic parameters predict post-call behaviour and whether these relationships vary by habitat quality, we will employ a multinomial GLMM. The response variable will be the categorical behavioural outcome, focusing on the five most frequent post-call behaviours observed during focal follows.Habitat quality (four levels: pristine, selectively logged, heavily logged, and degraded/fragmented), and their interactions. Including interaction terms will allow us to determine if habitat quality modifies the relationship between call structure and subsequent behaviour.

Additional covariates will include group size, time of day, temperature, and canopy density to account for environmental and social factors that might influence behavioural responses. Similar to our first hypothesis testing, we will include a nested random effects structure (Area/Individual/Day) to account for repeated observations of the same individuals and within the same study sites.

## Model Selection and Validation

For all models, we will employ an AIC-based model reduction approach to identify the simplest model that best explains the data. We will start with the full model containing all biologically relevant predictors and systematically remove one predictor at a time, retaining the model with the lowest AIC value at each step. This process will continue until removing variables no longer improves model fit.

Post-hoc comparisons among habitat quality levels will be conducted using Tukey's method with appropriate p-value adjustments for multiple comparisons. All statistical analyses will be performed in R (version 4.2.0 or later) using the lme4, nnet, glmmTMB, and DHARMa packages.

Preliminary Fieldwork Schedule

The audio moths need to be serviced every 10-14 days (new batteries and SD cards), meaning the sites need to be visited at regular intervals. Mangevo will require overnight expeditions as they are at remote locations in the rainforest. Talatakely and Sakaroa are reachable in a daytrip from the research centre. Depending on the fieldwork that needs to be carried out Valohoaka will be a mixture of daytrips and overnight expeditions. As Mangevo has an active, long term research project going on, there will be people available to service the Audiomoths, and it will require only two trips to deploy and collect Audiomoths, as well as to conducting focal follows. The days in which no fieldwork is scheduled serve as a buffer (in case expeditions take longer than expected), time to digitally enter, upload and backup data.

Data Storage and Sharing

To ensure the security, accessibility, and long-term usability of the data collected, a structured storage, backup, and sharing system will be implemented. Additionally, all data will be made openly accessible to support transparency and reproducibility in research.

Primary Data Storage

Audio data from the Audiomoth recorders and saved onto SD \*\*\*\*cards during fieldwork. Data from focal follows \*\*\*\*will be done on a digital behavioural platform and saved to the cloud when a WiFi connection is available. We estimate that we will need up to 10TB of storage on the cloud. Each Audiomoth will use approximately 7GB per day. We will also need 44 microSD cards of 128GB as each Audiomoth will require two cards. The minimum requirements for the SD cards is UHS speed class 3

Data Backup Strategy

Data from SD cards will be transferred to an external SSD to prevent loss due to equipment failure or environmental conditions. Whenever an internet connection is available, data will be uploaded to a cloud platform.

Data Organization and Metadata

Files will follow a standardized naming convention (e.g., date, location, recording unit ID). Metadata will include details on site conditions, recording settings, and observational context to ensure data usability.

Open Access and Data Sharing

Upon project completion, all cleaned datasets, along with metadata and relevant scripts, will be deposited in an open-access repository making it available for further research
